===from:Katie Ruchti
===email:ktsr1@hotmail.com
===date:Thu Jul 20 23:39:09 2000
===subject:Homework #6
===message:Topic #1

Yes, I would be tested. Not knowing is sometimes worse than knowing. At least if you knew you had the disease, you could enjoy what time you had left and do the things that you hope to in your life. Also, knowing the results would ultimately tell you whether or not you should have kids. If you didn't get tested and had children anyway, I do not feel that is being fair to that child since they too have a chance of inheriting the disease. If I got tested and the results were negative, you could live your life without having to always have in the back of your mind "what if"...
and if you find out you have the disease, you hope for a cure and just live your life to the fullest, although I am sure is not as easy as it sounds.

Topic 2

#1:  I think it's kind of creepy. I would rather just go buy a new dog than clone the old one. The old one may have been wonderful, but when the pet is gone, he's gone, and nothing is going to replace him.

#2:  Again, I would not do this. Cloning your child that has been killed is not going to make things any easier. This is a traumatic thing to go through. Trying to replace your child is only going to bring about more pain. A child that has the same genes and that looks the same as your first child may sound hopeful, but in the end, we cannot always just replace what we lose, life is much more precious than that.

#3:  This sounds good, but if I say this is okay, then it is just contradicting what I said in #2. I don't think we should clone his brain. What if it doesn't work? There are people in the world who are making great contributions to society right now and they were not cloned. We don't always need to look to the past. We have capable people who can make a difference that are living. Let Albert rest in peace.

#4:  Definitely not. I would rather clone Albert's brain than clone a bunch of little Michael Jordan's. I guess I am just stuck on the idea that every life is unique...someone like Michael Jordan has worked very hard to get to where he is today...he is a unique individual just as we all are unique in our own ways. I don't think people should be cloned...it seems to cheapen life and take away a person's individuality.
=========yorg=========
===from:Anita Vanlo
===date:Fri Jul 21 10:53:50 2000
===subject:Bio 109
===message:Topic 1--If one of my parents had Huntington's disease and I was in between the ages of 17-20, I wouldn't have myself tested unless I had symptoms of it. Considering that 17-20 is a fairly young age bracket, I don't believe that I would want to worry about death. Also, there is no cure for it,so I wouldn't want to live my life feeling like my existance was pointless, ending so soon, and knowing I was not going to be able to achieve my highest goals that come in time. Some people may argue that they would WANT to know if they had this disease, because they would try to live their life to the fullest and this disease would serve as mechanism for motivation. I believe that regardless if you have a disease or not you SHOULD live your life to the fullest and get motivated to do want you want for your own well-being. On the contrary, I believe that I would want to be tested before marriage if I decide to have children. When someone elses life would be at stake, I feel that the Huntington's disease would be a major concern. Since I don't plan on getting married until after the age of 20, the answer to the question "Would you have yourself tested?" would be "no", under such circumstances given.

Topic 2-- I don't believe that cloning would be justified in ANY scenario. Although it may be beneficial to society such as in Scenario 3, I still believe that it is immoral and is a selfish act. I must admit that I have more of a traditional point-of-view and not the "new perspective" outlook in this particular subject. Cloning is a very interesting, but debatable subject. I believe that Scenerio's 1,4, and regretfully 2 are outrageous, if not absurd. Cloning affects the rights of the diseased and all the laws of mankind. I live by the widely used expression,"if it was meant to be, it was meant to be". Cloning is a great scientific discovery and I commend whomever or WHATEVER helped to contribute to this discovery, but I still am faced with the question of morality. Let us live, die in peace, and keep all of our characteristics unique and special as we go on.  
=========yorg=========
