===message:Discussion topic 1:<BR>If one of my parents was found to have Huntington'sdisease, I would like to be tested to see if I had thedisease or not. Knowing what to do is better than doing something you are uncertain. Even that is knowing you are dying and deal with it earlier is better than notknowing when are you going to die. In fact, everyone hasto die, it is just the matter of time that how longyou can live. If the result indicates that I am normal,then my life will remain as normal as I was. Unfortunately,if I had the disease, I would get shocked at the firstplace, but I wouldn't act so passive. I wouldn't sitaround doing nothing and waiting to die. I would domany many things to make my life more meaningful. 10 years is more than enough for me to do everything I want.Also, I would not want to have children if I had the disease, 50% of the changes is too risky.<BR>Discussion topic 2:<BR>Scenario 1:<BR> I would like to clone my pet if I had the change. Iaccept cloning, but only for pets. I strongly disagreecloning human. Animals might have their own feelingas well, but due to communication restriction, we hardlyunderstand what they are trying to express. Therefore,we pretty much ignore them. Cloning animals isacceptable to me, because we don't have to deal withtheir feeling. For my pet, the cloned one would have myold dog genes, therefore it looks exactly alike. I amsure after certain periods, the personalities of the cloned dog are also same to my old dog. Since personality determines by gene and environment. If both factorsare the same, I see no reason why the cloned dog can'treplace my old dog. Which is for me, they are the same dog.<BR>Scenario 2: <BR>As I said before, I don't agree cloning human being. Evenif I had lost a son in accident. What makes human different from animals is that human has it own thinkingand life experience. Especially the experience we have,which makes us different from each other. We mighthave the same experience, but our own thinking makes ourperceptive different. Even a twin looks alike, we knowthey are entire two individuals. Same as cloning and theorigin. The cloned one can't never replace the old oneeven they look and act so much alike. This is becauseof memory. We can clone a body, but never can't copymemory of human. <BR>Scenario 3: <BR>Cloning a genius like Albert Einstein won't get theresult that we expect. Albert Einstein had greatcontributions to the world because of his efforts.If we clone a new one, he has no memory. Therefore, heis another person with high IQ in the world. No onecan ensure he is going to do the same thing what Albert Einstein did before. He might not interest inwhat Albert Einstein did. There are so many peoplewith high IQ out there, but not all of them areworking in research field.<BR>Scenario 4: <BR>People seem to forgoten the purpose of participatingsports. Performance is important, but not the most.The spirit of participating is what we are seeking.Cloning a person with good athelete ability like MJwill against the spirit of sports. Also it is unfairto others who put so much effort in their practice.We can't simple deprive other chances to participate just because we want to see high performance game.Therefore, cloning athletes is just not right to do.
